03999nam a22005535i 9780822376958DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223769587 a10.1515/97808223769582doi  a(DE-B1597)554215  a(OCoLC)1224279438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF3320b.A75 2014 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a984.05/12231 aAri, Waskar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEarth Politics :bReligion, Decolonization, and Bolivia's Indigenous Intellectuals /cWaskar Ari. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b19 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarrating Native Histories00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Building the Indian Law and a Decolonization Project in Bolivia -- tChapter Two. Nation Making and the Genealogy of the AMP Indigenous Activists -- tChapter Three. The Beginning of the Decolonization Project -- tChapter Four. Against Cholification -- tChapter Five. Between Internal Colonialism and War -- tChapter Six. Against Whitening -- tConclusion. The AMP's Innovations and Its Legacy in Bolivia under Evo Morales -- tAppendix 1 -- tAppendix 2 -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarth Politics focuses on the lives of four indigenous activist-intellectuals in Bolivia, key leaders in the Alcaldes Mayores Particulares (AMP), a movement established to claim rights for indigenous education and reclaim indigenous lands from hacienda owners. The AMP leaders invented a discourse of decolonization, rooted in part in native religion, and used it to counter structures of internal colonialism, including the existing racial systems. Waskar Ari calls their social movement, practices, and discourse earth politics, both because the AMP emphasized the idea of the earth and the place of Indians on it, and because of the political meaning that the AMP gave to the worship of the Aymara gods. Depicting the social worlds and life work of the activists, Ari traverses Bolivia's political and social landscape from the 1920s into the early 1970s. He reveals the AMP 's extensive geographic reach, genuine grassroots quality, and vibrant regional diversity. Ari had access to the private archives of indigenous families, and he collected oral histories, speaking with men and women who knew the AMP leaders. The resulting examination of Bolivian indigenous activism is one of unparalleled nuance and depth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIndians of South AmericazBoliviaxPolitics and government. 0aNationalismzBoliviaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376958zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376958.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles